<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>


<section xml:id="lesson3_3" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

  <title>Phase</title>
  <p>
    <term>Phase</term> is an additional attribute that is relevant when a qubit is in superposition.
    In the last section, you saw that if you have a circuit with two consecutive <c>H</c> gates, then
    the qubit goes into a superposition state after the <em>first</em>
    <c>H</c> gate, but then it goes
    back to its original state after the <em>second</em>
    <c>H</c> gate. The first <c>H</c> gate creates
    this superposition by transforming the basis states <m>\ket{0}</m> and <m>\ket{1}</m> into equal
    superpositions of both states, but with opposite phase. </p>

  <p> Phase is indicated with a positive (<m>+</m>) or negative (<m>-</m>) sign: </p>

  <sidebyside widths="70% 30%" valign="top">
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>If the state <m>\ket{0}</m> goes through an <c>H</c> gate, it has positive phase.</li>
        <li>If the state <m>\ket{1}</m> goes through an <c>H</c> gate, it has negative phase.</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <image source="NegativePhase.png" width="66%" />
  </sidebyside>

  <p> We depict this by placing a negative sign in front of the <m>⚫</m> outcome in the visual
    representation, as seen above.</p>

  <p> Why are positive and negative signs used to indicate phase? It turns out that to calculate
    the effect of different
    gates, or operations, using the positive and negative signs with existing algebraic rules
    results in the same behaviors
    that physicists observe in the real world. Since you already know algebra, you don't have
    to learn a whole new set of
    mathematical operations and symbols just to be able to calculate the behavior of quantum
    systems. </p>

  <p> Now that we have a visual representation of phase, we can have a more complete picture of what
    the <c>H</c> gate does to a qubit. The <c>H</c> gate creates a superposition of the input state,
    but the resulting phase depends on the input state. Additionally, when an <c>H</c> gate acts on
    an equal superposition state, the state returns to one of the basis states based on the phase of
    the superposition state. We can see that phase is an integral part of the quantum state; we will
    learn the detailed mathematics of this property later. </p>

  <image source="L3.2-H-with-phase.png" width="66%" />

  <p>For now, let's also introduce special terms for the two superposition states: <ul>
      <li><m>\ket{+}</m> for the state obtained after passing the <m>\ket{0}</m> state through an <c>H</c> gate</li>
      <li><m>\ket{-}</m> for the state obtained after passing the <m>\ket{1}</m> state through an <c>H</c> gate</li>
    </ul>
  </p>

  <section xml:id="sec-z-gate">
    <title><c>Z</c> Gate</title>

    <sidebyside widths="85% 15%" valign="top">
      <p> Now we are going to explore the <c>Z</c> gate, which affects the phase of the qubit. Use
        the circuit builder to determine how the <c>Z</c> gate affects a qubit that is in the state <m>
        \ket{0}</m>
        or <m>\ket{1}</m>. Construct the following two circuits and observe the outputs. </p>
      <image source="L3.3_Z-gate.png" width="30%" />
    </sidebyside>

    <image source="Z_Explore.png" width="20%" />
    <p>Remember that to create an input of <m>\ket{1}</m>, you will need to use a <c>NOT</c> gate.</p>


    <interactive aspect="9:9" platform="javascript"
      source="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/dmfranklin/quantum-module/source/loader.js">
      <script>
      visualizeProbabilitiesWidget({
        circuit: "Blank 1x6",
        allowedGates: "XHZ"
      });
    </script>
    </interactive>

    <exercise label="Z_truth_table_lesson3_3">
      <title>
        <c>Z</c> Truth Table </title>
      <idx>Z truth table</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>Which answer best describes what you observed from the <c>Z</c> gate? </p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>It does not have an observable effect.</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Correct!</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement>
            <p>If the input is <m>\ket{0}</m> or <m>\ket{1}</m>, the result will have an equal chance of measuring
              0 or 1. </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Look more closely at the bar graphs of the output.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>Make the circuit and look at the bar graph below the circuit. Construct both input
          combinations using <c>NOT</c> gates, recording the answers each time.</p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

    <p>
      You might have been surprised by the answer! Because quantum state is more complex than merely
      the probability of measuring 0 or 1, this method for determining and expressing an operation's
      functionality is insufficient.
    </p>
    <p> Now, use the circuit builder above to create the following circuits and observe the
      outcomes. This will reveal the functionality of the <c>Z</c> gate on a qubit in superposition. </p>

    <!--<alert><p>WHICH
    VERSION OF THESE CIRCUITS IS PREFERRED?
  I LIKE THIS ONE, B/C 0 AND 1 STATES ARE VERY CLEAR.
  THE CONVENTION ALSO MATCHES PRIOR LESSONS.
  ANOTHER OPTION WOULD BE TO INCLUDE BOTH HERE TO REMIND THEM OF THE CONVENTION? (jen)</p></alert>-->

    <image source="Z_Explore_2.png" width="50%" />

    <!--
  <p><em>(Remember that to create an input of <m>\ket{1}</m>, you will need to use a <c>NOT</c> gate,
    as shown here:)</em></p>
  <image source="Checkpoint3.2-Z-gate-behavior-with-Superposition.png" width="75%" />
  -->

    <exercise label="Superposition_Z">
      <title>
        <c>Z</c> Gate Behavior with Superposition </title>
      <idx>Superposition Z</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>What is the effect of the sequence <c>H</c>-<c>Z</c>-<c>H</c> on qubits beginning in <m>
          \ket{0}</m>
          or <m>
            \ket{1}
          </m>?</p>
        <image source="Checkpoint3.2-Z-gate-behavior-with-Superposition.png" width="66%" />
        <!--<image
        source="Z_Explore_2.png" width="50%" />-->
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement>
            <p>There is an equal chance of measuring 0 or 1.</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p> </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>No observable effect. </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p> </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>The same as a <c>NOT</c> gate</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Correct!</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>Think about what the output would be after each gate.</p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

    <p> Now we see that <c>Z</c> does have a major effect on the system, but <em>only</em> when the
      qubit is in superposition. Before we can understand how the <c>Z</c> gate works, let's first
      understand how gates work on states in superposition.</p>


  </section>

</section>
